## 4. World Handlers: `/home/openclaw/code/tuicraft/src/wow/world-handlers.ts`

### `handleContactList` (lines 517-543)

```typescript
export function handleContactList(conn: WorldConn, r: PacketReader): void {
  const list = parseContactList(r);
  const friends: FriendEntry[] = [];
  for (const contact of list.contacts) {
    if (!(contact.flags & SocialFlag.FRIEND)) continue;  // <-- filters out ignored
    const guidLow = Number(contact.guid & 0xffffffffn);
    const name = conn.nameCache.get(guidLow) ?? "";
    friends.push({ guid: contact.guid, name, note: contact.note,
                   status: contact.status ?? 0, area: contact.area ?? 0,
                   level: contact.level ?? 0, playerClass: contact.playerClass ?? 0 });
    if (!name && !conn.pendingNameQueries.has(`player:${guidLow}`)) {
      // ... sends CMSG_NAME_QUERY to resolve name
    }
  }
  conn.friendStore.set(friends);
}
```

The ignore list extension is a second loop in the same handler. For ignored contacts, name resolution is optional (names won't be in cache typically). The loop:
```typescript
const ignored: IgnoreEntry[] = [];
for (const contact of list.contacts) {
  if (!(contact.flags & SocialFlag.IGNORED)) continue;
  // ... build IgnoreEntry, optionally trigger name query
}
conn.ignoreStore.set(ignored);
```

### `handleFriendStatus` (lines 545-596)

This handler processes `SMSG_FRIEND_STATUS` for all social operations. Currently it routes to `conn.friendStore` based on `FriendResult` values. The `ADDED_ONLINE`/`ADDED_OFFLINE`/`ONLINE`/`OFFLINE`/`REMOVED` cases update the friend store; `default` fires a `friend-error` event.

For ignores, the server sends `SMSG_FRIEND_STATUS` with `result = FriendResult.ADDED_OFFLINE` (0x07) when adding an ignore (the person is "added" to the ignore list, always "offline" in terms of status fields). For removal, it sends `result = FriendResult.REMOVED` (0x05). The challenge is distinguishing whether the packet refers to a friend or ignore operation. The solution is to check if the GUID is in the `ignoreStore` for the `REMOVED` case, and to use context about which command was most recently sent. Looking at the WoW protocol, the server does not differentiate in `SMSG_FRIEND_STATUS` between friend and ignore operations — both use the same result codes.

The practical approach used by the reference client (`../wow-chat-client`) is to check the `ignoreStore` when handling `ADDED_OFFLINE` — if the operation came from `CMSG_ADD_IGNORE`, the store should handle it. A simple flag on `WorldConn` (`pendingIgnoreAdd: Set<string>`) tracks outgoing ignore operations.

### `deliverMessage` and `resolveAndDeliver` (lines 63-99)

```typescript
export function deliverMessage(conn: WorldConn, raw: RawChatMessage, name: string): void {
  conn.onMessage?.({ type: raw.type, sender: name, message: raw.message, channel: raw.channel });
}

export function resolveAndDeliver(conn: WorldConn, raw: RawChatMessage): void {
  if (raw.senderGuidLow === 0) { deliverMessage(conn, raw, ""); return; }
  const cached = conn.nameCache.get(raw.senderGuidLow);
  if (cached !== undefined) { deliverMessage(conn, raw, cached); return; }
  // ... pending name query
}
```

**This is where ignore filtering goes.** In `resolveAndDeliver`, before delivering, check if `conn.ignoreStore.has(raw.senderGuidLow)` and return early without delivering. This is the message suppression point. The filter goes before the `deliverMessage` call in both the cached and name-resolved paths.

